{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486948"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"214"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/214"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.09,0.13,0.02,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50474"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/214"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35691"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"254"},{"type":"tags","id":"255"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5605"},{"type":"tags","id":"11627"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42030"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50474"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient has just been intubated via rapid sequence induction in the resuscitation bay of an emergency department. The endotracheal tube was observed via video-laryngoscope to pass between the vocal cords.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is considered the gold-standard for confirming endotracheal intubation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Equal air entry on chest auscultation","Fogging on the plastic tubing","Visualisation of symmetrical chest wall rise and fall","No further confirmation required","Waveform capnography"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is vital following an intubation procedure to actively verify that the tube has passed into the trachea and not the oesophagus (its close posterior relation); unrecognised oesophageal intubation is lethal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIdeally, the tube has been directly observed during intubation to pass through the vocal cords and into the trachea. Nonetheless, further confirmatory assessments are required. Although no method is universally reliable, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewaveform capnography\u003C/strong\u003E (measuring concentration of expired carbon dioxide) is regarded as the best single method for confirming endotracheal tube placement. Whilst waveform capnography is the gold standard for confirmation of ETT placement in the trachea, it does not confirm ETT placement at the correct depth (e.g. inadvertent advancement of ETT into right main bronchus). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination including \u003Cstrong\u003Eauscultation\u003C/strong\u003E has been shown to be inadequately accurate (94% sensitive, 83% specific) and \u003Cstrong\u003Etube fogging\u003C/strong\u003E can still occur despite suboptimal placement. \u003Cstrong\u003EVisualisation of chest rise and fall\u003C/strong\u003E is also unreliable: visible chest wall mechanics are impacted by numerous factors including body habitus, injuries such as flail segments, and ventilator settings. Additionally, direct visualisation of passing the ETT between the cords can be reliably accurate however it should always be confirmed with another method as inadvertent oesophageal intubation can still occur. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce a capnography trace has been used to confirm that the tube is in the airway, usual practice is to perform a chest X-ray afterwards to assess whether position is optimum (i.e. not abutting the carina or passing into a bronchus). Chest X-ray is not used in the first instance, partly due to the delays this would entail, but also because of insufficient reliability as a sole technique.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note, capnography is less accurate in patients in cardiac arrest and other states of profoundly decreased perfusion. In these settings other strategies such as ultrasonography, direct visualisation, or an oesophageal detector device may be employed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Measurement of expired C02 concentrations is the surest way of ensuring correct endotracheal tube placement."],"references":["Reichman, EF 2013, Emergency medicine procedures, 2nd edn, McGraw-Hill, New York, \u2018Chapter 12. Confirmation of Endotracheal Intubation\u2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35691"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"214"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35691"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-12T14:46:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-12T14:46:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"214"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50474"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading"